The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Corporate Briefs

 Donear Industries has decided to issue bonus shares in 1:1 ratio, or one bonus share for every share held. The company has also proposed to split its equity shares in 1:5 ratio, that is every share having a face value of Rs 10 will be split into five equity of Rs 2 each, Donear has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. The Donear board has also recommended to increase the authorised share capital of the company to Rs 20 crore from Rs 11 crore at present. 

 Max India board has given its in principle approval for the amalgamation of Max Telecom Ventures, a wholly owned subsidiary, with itself. The board has adopted a resolution to this effect at a recently held meeting, the company has informed the stock exchanges. The board has also constituted a committee to finalise details and procedures for the scheme of amalgamation.

 LG Electronics will start manufacturing CDMA handsets in India next year and also scale up production capacity of GSM mobile phones to 10 million units by 2010 from one million at present. The company has opened its first one-stop service mall in New Delhi. The CDMA handsets will be manufactured at the company?s existing plant in Pune.

 Marsons will pump in Rs 8 crore this fiscal for expansion, mainly to build high voltage transformers. The company has also decided to double its authorised capital from Rs 11 crore to Rs 22 crore by creating 5.5 crore new shares of Rs 2 each during the next 12 months.

 Vyapar Industries will float a special purpose vehicle for setting up an apparel park in Andhra Pradesh. The SPV, which would be a subsidiary of the company, would start the park under the scheme for integrated SEZ Apparel Park 2005, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange.

 Suryavanshi Spinning Mills has decided to merge its garment manufacturing arm, Suryavanshi Textiles, with itself. The company?s board at its meeting two days ago has approved the merger proposal, which is subject to approval of shareholders, the company has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. 

 United Phosphorus will raise $150 millions by way of foreign currency convertible bonds (FCCBs) or other instruments. The company?s board has approved the issue of FCCBs, fully convertible debentures, partly convertible debentures and/or equity shares to raise the amount.

 Simbhaoli Sugar Mills will set up a new plant and expand crushing capacity of its Chilwara mill. The new plant will be set up in UP and will crush 4,500 tonnes of sugarcanes a day.

